<li id="cite_note-87"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-87">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite id="CITEREFRame1978" class="citation news cs1">Rame, George (June 14, 1978). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://newspapers.lib.utah.edu/details?id=28727961">"Blacks Eligible for LDS Temple Rites"</a>. <i><a href="/wiki/The_Salt_Lake_Tribune" title="The Salt Lake Tribune">The Salt Lake Tribune</a></i>. p.&#160;34. <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20230214001504/https://newspapers.lib.utah.edu/file?id=28727961">Archived</a> from the original on February 14, 2023 &#8211; via <a href="/wiki/University_of_Utah" title="University of Utah">University of Utah</a>. <q>So there is no ban on interracial marriage. If a black partner contemplating marriage is worthy of going to the Temple, nobody's going to stop him ... if he's ready to go to the Temple, obviously he may go with the blessings of the church.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=The+Salt+Lake+Tribune&amp;rft.atitle=Blacks+Eligible+for+LDS+Temple+Rites&amp;rft.pages=34&amp;rft.date=1978-06-14&amp;rft.aulast=Rame&amp;rft.aufirst=George&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fnewspapers.lib.utah.edu%2Fdetails%3Fid%3D28727961&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ABlack+people+and+Mormonism" class="Z3988"></span></span>
