<li id="cite_note-113"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-113">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite id="CITEREFAdams2012" class="citation journal cs1">Adams, Stirling (2012). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.jstor.org/stable/43201315">"The End of Bruce R. McConkie's "Mormon Doctrine"<span class="cs1-kern-right"></span>"</a>. <i>The John Whitmer Historical Association Journal</i>. <b>32</b> (2). <a href="/wiki/John_Whitmer_Historical_Association" title="John Whitmer Historical Association">John Whitmer Historical Association</a>: 59–69. <a href="/wiki/ISSN_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="ISSN (identifier)">ISSN</a>&#160;<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.worldcat.org/issn/0739-7852">0739-7852</a>. <a href="/wiki/JSTOR_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="JSTOR (identifier)">JSTOR</a>&#160;<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.jstor.org/stable/43201315">43201315</a> &#8211; via <a href="/wiki/JSTOR" title="JSTOR">JSTOR</a>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=The+John+Whitmer+Historical+Association+Journal&amp;rft.atitle=The+End+of+Bruce+R.+McConkie%27s+%22Mormon+Doctrine%22&amp;rft.volume=32&amp;rft.issue=2&amp;rft.pages=59-69&amp;rft.date=2012&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.jstor.org%2Fstable%2F43201315%23id-name%3DJSTOR&amp;rft.issn=0739-7852&amp;rft.aulast=Adams&amp;rft.aufirst=Stirling&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.jstor.org%2Fstable%2F43201315&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ABlack+people+and+Mormonism" class="Z3988"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-114"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-114">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite id="CITEREFRamirez2005" class="citation news cs1">Ramirez, Margaret (July 26, 2005). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.chicagotribune.com/chi-blackmormons-story.html">"Mormon past steeped in racism"</a>. <i><a href="/wiki/Chicago_Tribune" title="Chicago Tribune">Chicago Tribune</a></i>. <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20220407122211/https://www.chicagotribune.com/chi-blackmormons-story.html">Archived</a> from the original on April 7, 2022 &#8211; via <a href="/wiki/Internet_Archive" title="Internet Archive">Internet Archive</a>. <q>Discredited doctrines about why some people are black have continued to circulate among Mormon whites in various places, despite the fact that no church leaders have taught such things for at least a whole generation,' [Armand] Mauss said. 'Old dogmas die hard.' Asked why leaders have not formally repudiated the teachings, spokeswoman Kim Farah referred to a statement made by Hinckley in 1998: 'The 1978 revelation continues to speak for itself ... I don't see anything further that we need to do.'<span class="cs1-kern-right"></span></q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Chicago+Tribune&amp;rft.atitle=Mormon+past+steeped+in+racism&amp;rft.date=2005-07-26&amp;rft.aulast=Ramirez&amp;rft.aufirst=Margaret&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.chicagotribune.com%2Fchi-blackmormons-story.html&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ABlack+people+and+Mormonism" class="Z3988"></span></span>
</li>
